tion).\n- Not very willing to further his education (potential limitation for long\u2011term development).\n**Candidate\u202fD**\n- Responds adequately to unexpected events (adaptability under pressure).\n- Can concentrate very well (focus).\n- Solves problems extremely well (technical problem\u2011solving).\n- Takes responsibility seriously (sense of duty).\n- Regarded as a *know\u2011it\u2011all* (temperament that may alienate crew).\n- Has a hot temper (risk of deteriorating crew dynamics under stress).\n- Considered moody (temperament stability concerns).\n- Regarded as a loner (potential challenge for crew integration).\n**Preliminary synthesis**\n- **Candidate\u202fC** combines rapid, correct decision\u2011making, strong stress resilience, high conscientiousness, solid technical understanding, and a proven ability to foster a positive crew atmosphere. The main drawbacks are communication difficulty and an egocentric streak, but these are less safety\u2011critical than the interpersonal and reliability concerns seen in the other candidates.\n- **Candidate\u202fB** offers excellent calmness and reliability but has clear teamwork and temperament red flags (nasty remarks, grumpiness, weak numeric memory).\n- **Candidate\u202fA** shows strong situational awareness and leadership but suffers from inflexibility, poor receptiveness to criticism, and health/temperament issues that could impair long\u2011haul crew harmony.\n- **Candidate\u202fD** is technically strong and responsible but displays a hot temper, know\u2011it\u2011all attitude, and loneliness that could jeopardize crew cohesion on extended flights.\nGiven the full set of attributes, **Candidate\u202fC** remains the most balanced choice for a long\u2011distance, high\u2011responsibility pilot role. I welcome any additional positive attributes for the other candidates that might shift this assessment.\nMETADATA_JSON:\n{\"agent\": \"agent_1\", \"vote\": \"Candidate C\"}", "thoughts": "We need to produce final